IS it really worth buying that lottery ticket? Are you sure those overpriced things you can&rsquo;t really afford will improve your life?1.&nbsp;Lottery tickets Yes, there have been people who have won the lottery &ndash; we&rsquo;re not denying that. But winning the actual jackpot is about a one in 24 435 180 chance. You may waste a lot of money on extra tickets &ndash; but this doesn&rsquo;t improve your odds very much. 2.&nbsp;Clothes that cost more than your groceries I know. It&rsquo;s not easy to say no to yourself when you see that new pair of shoes or outfit. But, before you do, consider the following: do you need the item of clothing in your life right now? Is it an investment piece that you&rsquo;re going to wear more than once? No one is saying that you shouldn&rsquo;t treat yourself or spoil yourself with a gorgeous item or two, but do your research about trends &ndash; shop smartly, never on impulse!3.&nbsp;Year-long subscription services that you don&rsquo;t really use A few years ago two friends joined a gym. For the first few weeks all went well &ndash; they were motivated and driven to attend. But slowly and surely a missed gym day became a missed week, and then a missed month &ndash; until the pair stopped going. But they were still paying for membership. Unless you&rsquo;re willing to commit to a service you know you&rsquo;re going to use, avoid signing up for something you&rsquo;re only going to end up wasting money on. Don&rsquo;t want to gym but you want to up your fitness game? Buy fitness DVDs or search for tutorials online. Buzzfeed.com has compiled a list of some of the best health and wellness channels to check out, so rather invest in data, if you don&rsquo;t trust yourself to commit to a gym. 4.&nbsp;Decorative items that won&rsquo;t pay the bills (Go DIY instead) Of course we want our homes to be open, welcoming and beautiful. But, unless you can afford to buy high-end decor features, it&rsquo;s time to get in touch with your crafty side and go the DIY route. Make decor items &ndash; don&rsquo;t buy them. And if you&rsquo;re new to the DIY game, do some research to get your creative juices flowing. Not only is it a cheaper option, it&rsquo;s also much more fun.5.&nbsp;Don&rsquo;t get caught in the sale trap Who doesn&rsquo;t love a good bargain? The problem with sales is that people often end up buying a whole lot of things they don&rsquo;t need &ndash; simply because it&rsquo;s on sale. Also, because you&rsquo;re getting it cheap, you convince yourself you can buy more &ndash; simply because it&rsquo;s on special.In the end, the money you think you&rsquo;re saving only goes into more stuff, and that defeats the purpose.